"Society tends to flit from hysteria to hysteria," said Pat Michaels, Virginia's state climatologist and moderator of the symposium.
"I'm worried ... that when the next drought happens, we are going to have to rediscover the climate problem," said Michaels, president of the Association of State Climatologists.
However, David Rodenhuis, director of the federal Climate Analysis Center in Washington, said he was skeptical of Plummer's thesis.
"There's an enormous number of possibilities that one could chase," Rodenhuis said.
